===Etymology 2===
{{zh-forms|alt=子-chiefly in place names,囝,兒,亜,啊,也-after name or title}}
{{ncog|nan-hbl|仔|tr=á}} is historically a weak form of {{m|nan-hbl|囝|tr=kiáⁿ, kó̤aⁿ}}, as evidenced in older, less reduced forms such as:
* {{m|nan-hbl|仔|tr=giá, giáⁿ}}, as per ''Dictionario Hispanico Sinicum'' (1626-1642), {{w|zh:彙音妙悟|《彙音妙悟》}}(''{{w|nan:Lūi-im Biāu-ngō͘|Lūi-im Biāu-ngō͘}}'') (1800), and Van der Loon (1967).
* {{m|nan-hbl|仔|tr=iá, iáⁿ}}, as per ''Dictionario Hispanico Sinicum'' (1626-1642), Medhurst (1832), and Van der Loon (1967).
* {{m|nan-hbl|仔|tr=ngiá/ngiáⁿ, ngá/ngáⁿ}}, as per ''Dictionario Hispanico Sinicum'' (1626-1642), Van der Loon (1967), and Douglas (1873).
* {{m|nan-hbl|仔|tr=niá/niáⁿ, ná/náⁿ}}, as per ''Dictionario Hispanico Sinicum'' (1626-1642) and Douglas (1873).
The latter two in particular with [[nasal]] [[initial]]s usually occur after [[syllable]]s ending in a [[nasalized]] [[rime]] (Van der Loon 1967; Douglas 1873) due to possibly being a result of nasal [[assimilation]]. Also, in [[Pe̍h-ōe-jī]] (POJ), syllables with a nasal initial [[allophonically]] have a nasalized [[vowel]] or not, as per Van der Loon (1967), though the above are shown with a [[nasalization]] symbol (i.e.〈ⁿ〉) as used by Douglas (1873) in order to fully portray the recorded historical [[antecedent]]s.

See also modern {{ncog|nan-qua|囝|tr=káⁿ|pos=[[IPA]]: [kã⁵⁵⁴]}}, which came from the historical {{lg|archaic}} form {{ncog|nan-qua|囝|tr=kó̤aⁿ|pos=[[IPA]]: [kɯã⁵⁵⁴]}}, still used in traditional {{l|nan-hbl|南管|tr=Lâm-koán}} opera, as per 《當代泉州音字彙》(2012).

Mandarin and Cantonese pronunciations in words borrowed from Southern Min are from etymology 1.

